Remove "Discretionary" as a travel cat option

comments.body:
Ok, I take it back, looking at how this is created in the database, I don't think there's a way to remove it from the database as an option. From [the PostgreSQL documentation](https://www.postgresql.org/docs/current/datatype-enum.html):

> Existing values cannot be removed from an enum type, nor can the sort ordering of such values be changed, short of dropping and re-creating the enum type.

I'm not sure it's worth dropping and re-creating the column for this? What do you think @christinach and @kevinreiss ? See [this stack overflow answer](https://stackoverflow.com/a/25812436) for an all-sql example.

Hrm, and then the [Rails ActiveRecord documentation for Enum](https://api.rubyonrails.org/v6.1.7.2/classes/ActiveRecord/Enum.html) doesn't say anything about migrations, but only talks about the definition in the class, which this PR changes as suggested.

> Therefore, once a value is added to the enum array, its position in the array must be maintained, and new values should only be added to the end of the array. **To remove unused values, the explicit hash syntax should be used.**
I don't think it's worth investing time to alter the database. We should just add a commit that removes the choice for the interface.

pdc_discovery.title: Make sure reindex is scheduled only in one server
Possible caching issue when using widgets to filter

comments.body:
I did a bit more digging and it seems that our reindex process is indeed having issues with the replication which is what causes the number of total documents to flip flop between two values, for example between 142 vs 367. 

We are currently not experiencing this issue in production because we are locked to a single replica but this is not a good long term plan.

Forcing the reindex to target the "leader" node seems to fix this problem ([details here](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1OQO1NEXxoEfltPkx1dBuMVqvOJbCxc-6_GQ1YSOaSsM/edit)) but we shouldn't have to do this.
